^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let me discuss the auction. The bids through 2@H are fine. Then Ruth needs to decide what to do. Ruth has a very nice hand, especially in clubs. A club slam is very possible. A heart slam might be possible as well, but with such nice clubs, it is likely clubs will play at least as well, and probably better, than hearts.|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The problem is, Ruth has only 1 key card and if you use 4NT to ask about key cards they could easily get too high if they are missing 3 key cards. In general playing 2/1, 4@C over 2@H is not a good bid because the idea is to go slowly once a game force is established. Having said that, an expert might very well bid 4@C with Ruth's hand, for the following reasons.|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The message being conveyed by 4@C is "Partner I have a self sufficient club suit and I am very interested in slam. Just start control bidding." Ruth in particular is worried about spades. |
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So a possible expert auction might start as 1@H-2@C-2@H-4@C. Then Jacquie would bid 4@D and Ruth would bid 4@H. Finally, Jacquie, lacking a spade control would bid 5@C and the auction would end there.|
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If Jacquie bid 4@S over 4@H then Ruth might venture 6@C, hoping that they have enough key cards. But it is very difficult to bid slam in a minor playing RKCB because the responses over 4NT might get the partnership too high which is why some expert partnerships play an ace asking convention known as "^*BKickback^*N."|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If you played kickback (and I don't suggest you do) then the suit one higher than the trump suit is used as the Key Card Ask. Therefore, if you were in a potential club slam auction, 4@D would be the Key Card Ask playing Kickback.|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|And (using 0314 scheme) the response steps would be: 
Step 1 4@H ^e= 0 or 3 Key Cards, 
Step 2 4@S ^e= 1 or 4 Key Cards, 
Step 3 4N  ^e= 2 Key Cards - no trump queen and
Step 4 5@C ^e= 2 Key Cards - with trump queen.|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|That way, if the partnership did not have enough Key Cards they could still end up playing 5@C.|
PG| ***** 18 ***** |


AT|
duffer66: Kickback has to be at 4 level?  |
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


cp|8|AT|^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Yes, if you play kickback 
4@D ^C= Key Card Ask in clubs, 
4@H ^C= Key Card Ask in diamonds, 
4@S ^C= Key Card Ask in hearts, 
4N  ^C= Key Card Ask in spades.|
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But, as I said, I don't recommend you play it. I play it with one partner and often I am confused as to whether his bid is kickback, a control bid, or natural. We don't have a good record of bidding slams.|
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now as to the auction as it went. Over 3@C, Jacquie's 3@D bid was a good bid, asking Ruth to bid 3N with a spade stopper. Ruth decided 4@H was a better contract. And by bidding 4@H rather than 3@H, showed little slam interest. As to whether or not Jacquie should bid 5@C, I am not sure. |
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|It is likely Ruth only has 2 hearts with some honor. With 3 hearts, Ruth would have either bid 3@H (or 4@H) over 2@H or 3@H over 3@D. And since Ruth repeated her clubs, Jacquie knows Ruth has a nice 6+ card suit most likely. So Kxx is great support and 5@C is certainly a reasonable bid.|
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The only issue she needs to think about is it is harder to take 11 tricks than 10 tricks. But it is hard to know for sure whether 4@H or 5@C is a better contract. She should suspect 2 spade losers which means their side can't lose any other tricks. Whereas in 4@H they can lose 3 tricks. |
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So in general you try to avoid playing 5 of a minor when another alternative (3NT or 4 of a major) is available. On this hand, 5@C could easily be right as it turns out, both 4@H and 5@C makes. In IMPs 5@C and 4@H is pretty much irrelevant. In MPs it is relevant. |
