^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|First the bidding. First of all, you have to decide, when playing 2/1 if 1N by a passed hand is still forcing. I personally like to play it is, but many play it non-forcing or semi-forcing. For those who play it non-forcing (and do not play Drury) Liza has to bid 2@C because she has a 3-card limit raise.|
PG| ***** 87 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|It turns out even if you play Drury, you bid 2@C but that is a different discussion. Let me skip Drury for the moment and discuss why I like 1N as forcing even by a passed hand. There are often hands where you want 1N to be forcing when you have less than an opener such as a 3-card limit raise, as Liza had or a weak hand with a long suit. |
PG| ***** 88 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So I like playing 1N as forcing. Some people play a convention known as Drury. It is particularly useful if you play light 3rd seat openers (which I do not usually do). Drury works as follows.|
PG| ***** 89 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If partner opens 1 of a major in 3rd seat, 2@C and 2@D are both artificial bids. 2@C shows a 3-card limit raise (such as Liza's hand, her clubs are irrelevant if playing Drury). 2@D shows a 4-card limit raise. If opener rebids their suit, it shows a sub-minimum opener. Otherwise they have to bid something other than 2 of their suit. I am not a big fan of Drury, but many experts love it.|
PG| ***** 90 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|One comment on the play. At trick 1 Jacquie should play the @CJ that way she guarantees 3 club tricks regardless of who has the @CQ and makes 6.|
PG| ***** 91 ***** |


